The discharged blood from the uterus during the reproductive years. The discharge occurs approximately once a month.
The air that moves out of the chest during expiration. It contains a higher percentage of carbon dioxide and a lower percentage of oxygen compared to the inhaled air.

The newborn's first intestinal discharge. It is a dark-green, thick substance composed of mucus, intestinal secretions, hair, and intestinal mucosa cells.
The fluid that passes through the wall of the veins and capillaries to the surrounding tissues because of increased intravascular pressure. It has low protein content.

A drug pack that contains a 21 day supply of tablets, composed of a mixture of active and/or inert ingredient(s) that are pressed or compacted into a solid round, square or oval shaped form.
A drug pack that contains a 28 day supply of tablets, composed of a mixture of active and/or inert ingredient(s) that are pressed or compacted into a solid round, square or oval shaped form.

A solution or suspension taken orally and moved around the back of the throat by tilting the head back and forcing air from the lungs through the solution. Unless specifically directed, the solution is expelled and not swallowed.
A semi-solid that is oily and viscous and composed of a hydrocarbon based resin formed from the breakdown and distillation of organic substances.

A tablet designed to release active and/or inert ingredient(s) slowly so as to achieve a constant circulating concentration of the ingredient over a period of time.
A cap for a medication that contains a memory device designed to indicate if the medication has been taken.
A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained usually in a syringe or a small cup and is to be administered in full at once.
An anhydrous calcium salt form of atorvastin, a synthetic lipid-lowering agent.
